   <mods:abstract>Necker's return has not restored the expected tranquillity. There has been
            some violence in Paris, where a few rioters were killed by the city militia. Baron de
            Besenval and the Duke de la Vauguyon, who were trying to flee, were captured and
            imprisoned. Luzerne continues in his position, and others like the Archbishop of
            Bordeaux, De la Tour de Pin, and the Prince of Beauvau have been named to the ministry.
            The National Assembly is at work on a declaration of rights. Jefferson fears that the
            number of those called by Necker to the meeting, one thousand two hundred persons, will
            make the formulation of the law difficult. The desire of the Parisians to form a
            municipal government independent of the authority of the nation at large may be a danger
            to the unity of the country.</mods:abstract>
